cum inscribere nomen non liceret: so Ktih. Sff. Ml. TS. nomen is not in the MSS. It was restored by Ernesti, non—2, i.e. nomen, having fallen out before non. As sculptors often inscribed their names upon their works, and Phidias himself (cf. Pausanias v 10 p. 397) actually in- scribed his name at the feet of his Olympian Zeus, many have read cum inscribere nomen licea-el. But Klotz, quoted in liuh„ notes that many ancient statues have been discovered in Paris to contain the name of the sculptor carefully concealed within them with a statement that the artists were not allowed to append their names openly. WVhence Klotz conjectures that it rested with the patron or authority, who ordered the statue, to allow or forbid the inscription of the name.

sua nomina inscribunt: cf. p. Areh. 11, 26 for the same thought.
